##We are Wuhan citizens and want to do something for the city

Micro signal

Function description, we are with you in this battle

Public Transport in Wuhan was suspended on January 23. Some local private car owners decided to escort medical staff to and from work free of charge, and to deliver relief supplies to major hospitals. The 34-year-old car is one of them.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Wu Meifen

Since the end of January, the car has run through nearly every hospital in Wuhan, delivering supplies donated by the public to medical staff.

When I got in the car on February 6th, he said I could talk to him if I wanted to remain anonymous. He didn't think what he was doing was worth mentioning, and he didn't want his family to know he was doing it for fear that they would worry.

Here's what the car says:

A note from the doctor

I am a native of Hunan Province. I started my own business in Wuhan. I have lived in this city for more than ten years and have deep feelings for it.

In mid-january, several people in the family have a fever, 14 I went to the community hospital to see a doctor, 15 to take the children to see the Pediatric Union Hospital. No matter which hospital, a doctor heard is a fever, asked recently to the South China Seafood Market?

Car Friend Zone

At that time the hospital has seen the fever many people, listens to the lung sound and the blood test line is very long. The doctor is my friend, revealed to me that usually to do a good job of protection, wearing a mask and so on. He didn't say exactly what it was, but he did warn me.

I don't watch much news. A lot of it comes from my doctor friends. Around January 23, I was considering whether to take my family back to my hometown in Hunan Province, but decided to stay. Wuhan is already my home, no matter where I go, I always remember here, so we did not go home.

My little friends and I have been doing public welfare in Wuhan for many years.

Last year, during a rainstorm and flood in Wuhan, the road was flooded and many cars could not get through. Our motorcade spontaneously organized rescue missions to bring food to some primary schools. We also went to College Station, Pak Sha Chau, to transport waves of college students trapped inside. We'd love to do something for the city.

At the end of January, several friends told me that the hospital was in short supply, so we thought we would help by raising money to buy masks, protective clothing and other medical supplies for the hospital. We are responsible for the delivery of supplies to the hospital, Wuhan so many hospitals, including concord, the Red Cross, the provincial people, Zhongnan Hospital, and so on, almost every one has gone through.

On the 2nd and 3rd, I delivered supplies to the Red Cross Hospital. At this time, the hospital entrance has been fenced off, can not enter. I had to call the doctor who received the supplies, and when the call went unanswered, I thought he might be trying to save the patient, and didn't dare to keep trying.

Then, seeing a doctor pass by at the door, he stopped him. He was in a hurry, too, responding in a particularly urgent tone. I told him why I was here, and I gave him the supplies. He told me he would never lose it, that it would be in the hands of the doctor I contacted.

I told him, these supplies are for you angels in White, no matter who end up in the hands of, it does not matter, as long as the role of play, I feel good.

At that time many big hospitals are sending the material shortage appeal announcement, the society can see their information, is paying attention to them.

But there are some small hospitals that don't get noticed at all.

"I had a nervous breakdown. I sat on the curb and cried for hours. "

On February 4th, I went to a very small hospital, called Puren Hospital, which also has a lot of patients. I called the doctor I contacted and waited at the door.

After 10 minutes, the doctor came down, and I saw that he wasn't wearing a doctor's suit, and there was no mask on his face. I didn't ask him why, but I don't think he didn't want to wear it, maybe not enough or not enough. I didn't want to hold him up, so I didn't check with him, just handed it to him.

He took it and bowed to me. This one, let me accept very hard, my mood collapsed, squatted on the roadside to cry for a long time.

He thanked me for the first-line medical staff under such difficult circumstances. Later, he added my Wechat, but also kept to say thank you. Actually, we should be thanking him.

On February 2, I went to Concord Hospital to deliver supplies, and a doctor in the Department of Supplies told me that the government now asked them to provide 700 additional beds, but in the end they only opened 200. He said: "I would like to open 700, but really can not open, not enough supplies, can not let my doctors and nurses go up to see patients naked. ".

We met at the Western Union, and he came down with some doctors to get supplies, and I saw that these doctors were wearing normal surgical masks, not protective clothing.

When I went to the hospital, I was wearing a full suit of protective clothing, wrapped up in a tight, those doctors looked at me, cast is that kind of envious eyes. I'm wearing goggles. They don't even have goggles.

I urge the community to distribute N95 masks to first-line medical personnel. I know a lot of people need help, but these doctors are the ones who are the most pathetic right now. Doctors are on the front lines helping patients, coming home from work, and some of their families are infected.

It's like, I go to the hospital to deliver supplies, and I'm very protective, and it's to protect my family.

On January 31, the car delivered sterile water to the Kong Hon Community Hospital

On January 29, I was in Hankou Hospital and Xinhua Hospital, and I saw a lot of medical staff wearing thick three-layer protective clothing, wearing three-layer gloves and isolation mask, constantly walking to inject patients and care, work very hard.

Doctors who live too far away can not go home, so the hospital arranges dormitories or hotels for them, such as the three hospitals and the Provincial People's Hospital. There are also many doctors and nurses choose not to go back to rest temporarily, the body can not bear, just wear protective clothing to take turns to rest for half an hour. Nothing, because if you take off your suit, it's contaminated.

To save on protective clothing, they sleep in their chairs during the break, sometimes lying on the floor, sleeping for half an hour and getting back to work. This is a very normal state in the hospital, a very sincere state for the patients, quite moved.

At the end of January, doctors at a hospital in Wuhan took a break in protective clothing

I've also tried wearing protective clothing all day without taking it off, not eating, not drinking, not going to the bathroom, and it's really hard. Protective clothing is not breathable at all, goggles whether with saliva or hand sanitizer to wipe, wear for a long time will have fog, not clear. N95 Mask. I wear it for two hours, I can't stand it. I'm dizzy from lack of oxygen. Doctors wear them for four, five hours, all day.

On the second day of the Lunar New Year, I went to the third hospital to give a doctor friend something to eat and drink. He has been working for about ten hours straight. He was moved to tears when he saw my supplies.

He is my friend, we often eat together, usually he is a very strong person, rarely shed tears.

He looked haggard. We didn't talk much. I didn't want to waste his time, either. I was just dropping off supplies. Life is important. There are patients in every bed, and maybe one or two of US will die while we're talking.

We don't ask for receipts, invoices, anything like that. We're individual donors. Any doctor who wants to be on camera, just take a picture and tell the donor what happened. As long as we can prove that the doctor took the supplies, it's okay if you don't want to show your face.

The vehicles delivered supplies to Puai Hospital and the First Hospital of Hubei Province

My family can't know I'm volunteering

These days in Wuhan city running, the road is less than before, see almost all the cars are volunteers, before a busy city, now it is very quiet, people feel sad, like a dream.

Elsewhere in the city, we didn't pay much attention to it, just focused on quickly, quickly loading, quickly loading the car, quickly to the hospital, can run an additional hospital, can help more doctors.

I can't let my family know I'm doing this. They'll go crazy.

When I needed to deliver supplies, I would make excuses to go out and buy food or exercise in the underground garage. After all, it's not easy to buy food these days. Sometimes I have to buy medicine. Many pharmacies are not open, so it takes a little longer and my family doesn't suspect anything. I want you to go home as soon as you're done delivering supplies. If I wasn't married, had no kids, and had no parents, I'd probably be leaving early and coming home late to take the doctor to and from work, just like my friends.

My family's in quarantine these days. They are very optimistic, I have a one-year-old child, everyone's heart is in this innocent child, will not be bored.

People Call US volunteers, but we don't like it. We are a part of this city, a citizen of Wuhan.

We just see the status quo and want to do something about it according to our own ideas and abilities. If we can't, we answer our country's call and stay at home. We know exactly what we're doing, and we know how to protect ourselves.

Armored car

We don't like to be called volunteers, either, because being a "volunteer" can be so morally hostage.

A few of my friends have been interviewed by the media, they feel that they have been morally kidnapped. Because people will expect you to do things that they think you should do. We don't like and don't like to be told what to do or what to do.

A friend of mine drives a doctor to and from work every day, and after it was reported in the news media, a lot of people came to him, hoping they could help. There are communities that want to help transport patients, and there are families who want to call and help their families get hospitalized. You know, my friend doesn't talk to the doctor when he's driving him to and from the hospital, so how does that help a patient stay there.

Some of the foreigners responsible for evacuating overseas Chinese came to us, hoping to pick up their compatriots, and we also refused. Our abilities are limited, and it's unlikely that we'll be able to help anyone with more than a doctor to pick us up and drop us off.

Now, I cough because of Pharyngitis, causing costal cartilage inflammation, the doctor's diagnosis may be a fracture, playing bandage at home to recover from the injury did not go out. I've been in so many hospitals, I'm at risk of infection, and I've been home in quarantine for a while.

Part of me wishes I could do more. I've had volunteers die of infections. I want to protect my people, too.

As we all know, there are risks involved in choosing to do this, and it's hard to watch volunteers die. But the more it is, the more we have to work together to restore our city as early as possible to the hustle and bustle of the past.

Of course, we will pay attention to safety, not only do a good job of protection, but also try to eat on time every day to ensure nutrition and resistance.

Now, my ability is not good, back down to protect themselves, I also have a family, there are old and young, responsible to them. That's how I really feel.

("Che Che" is an alias)
